      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "25–31. Threat of Exile with Promise of Grace on Repentance",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "If, with the slackness of increasing years, Israel give way to idolatry (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") Moses testifies that they shall perish from the land (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and be scattered among the peoples (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") where indeed they must worship senseless idols (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). So far the Pl. address. But if—change to the Sg.—in these latter days of tribulation the nation seeks and returns to Jehovah it shall find Him (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:29",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " f.). He will not fail nor forget His covenant (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:31",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ").—As we shall see from the notes the threat of exile is no sufficient ground for judging ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:25-28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " to be an exilic addition, but there are several phrases which only D and P have. Others are found only in xxviii. The exilic origin of 29–31 is more probable. Dillm. denies a connection between ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and the preceding; it seems to the present writer that ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:25-28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is a natural continuation of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:23",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Deuteronomy 4:23",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". This, however, by itself does not prove identity of authorship.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Further Note on",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "25–31",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The two parts of this ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:25-28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:29-31",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " are probably separate; note the change of address. Berth. says that the whole ‘bears clearly the stamp of exilic authorship.’ This is not true of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:25-28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", the threat of exile. After the exile of N. Israel in 721 and the precedents in prophecy for a threat of exile (cp. Amos, Isaiah and Jeremiah), and the notorious policy of Assyria towards subject races, it would on the contrary have been strange not to have found in the pre-exilic deuteronomists, with their prophetic temper, some foreboding of exile. Dillm. rightly says, ‘the threat of exile has nothing surprising in it,’ if we compare ch. 28. But the case is different with the promise contingent on the conversion of the people in exile. In itself it is as conceivable in D as in the prophets (whom it is impossible to regard, as a powerful school of criticism does, as predicters only of judgement), but as Dillm. points out it lies here too far away from the purpose of the exhortation1[115]. Add to this reasons of form, (1) that the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "for",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " introducing ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:32",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ff. has no relevancy to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:29-31",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", but continues ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:25-28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (see Driver), and (2) the change from the Pl. to the Sg. address—and there is a strong case for taking ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:29-31",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " as a later exilic insertion like ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 30:1-10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Berth.’s argument that ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:32",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " naturally follows ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:24",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Deuteronomy 4:24",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is met by the fact that it more naturally follows ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:28",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Deuteronomy 4:28",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and we have already seen that ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:25-28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " are the natural continuation of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:23",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Deuteronomy 4:23",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". We may, therefore, take ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:25-28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " as integral, and only ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:29-31",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " as a later exilic intrusion.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "[115] There is an analogy, however, in 29 f.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
